{{Infobox Korean name | hangul = 만경대상국제마라손경기대회 | hanja = 萬景臺賞國際마라손競技大會 | rr = Man-gyeongdaesang-gukje-marason-gyeonggidaehoe | mr = Man'gyŏngdaesang-gukche-marason-gyŏnggidaehoe | context = north | image = Participants in the 2012 Pyongyang Marathon running past the Arch of Triumph.jpg | caption = Participants in the 2012 Pyongyang Marathon running past the [[Arch of Triumph (Pyongyang)|Arch of Triumph]]. }}
'''Pyongyang Marathon''', also known as '''Mangyongdae Prize International Marathon''', is an annual [[marathon]] race contested each April in [[Pyongyang]], the capital of [[North Korea]]. It is categorised as an [[IAAF Bronze Label Road Race]].
The marathon was held for the first time in 1981 for men, and the women's event was initiated in 1984.<ref>Korea Today: [http://www.kcckp.net/de/periodic/todaykorea/index.php?contents+4078+2009-03+119+28 Mangyongdae Prize International Marathon Race]{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The 2009 race was the 22nd event.<ref>Korean Central News Agency: April 12, 2009: [http://www.kcna.co.jp/item/2009/200904/news12/20090412-17ee.html Mangyongdae Prize Marathon Race Held] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090610172744/http://www.kcna.co.jp/item/2009/200904/news12/20090412-17ee.html |date=2009-06-10 }}</ref> The competition was opened for international runners again in 2000. The race starts and finishes at the [[Rungnado May Day Stadium]] or [[Kim Il-sung Stadium|Kim Il Sung Stadium]] and runs along the [[Taedong River]].<ref>Jalava, Mirko (2011-04-11). [http://www.iaaf.org/LRR11/news/newsid=59749.html Marusin and Ro take the wins in Pyongyang]. IAAF. Retrieved on 2011-04-12.</ref> At the 2010 edition of the race, Ukrainian [[Ivan Babaryka]] became the first European runner to win in Pyongyang in 24 years.<ref>Jalava, Mirko (2010-04-12). [http://www.iaaf.org/LRR10/news/newsid=56452.html Surprise victory by Babaryka in Pyongyang – Mangyongdae Prize Marathon report]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2010-04-12.</ref> The race in 2012 was held as part of celebrations for the 100 years since [[Kim Il-sung]]'s birth and featured one of the race's closest ever finishes: [[Oleksandr Matviychuk]] and [[Pak Song-chol (athlete)|Pak Song-chol]] were given identical times (2:12:54 hours), with the Ukrainian guest taking the title.<ref>Jalava, Mirko (2012-04-09). [http://www.iaaf.org/Mini/LRR12/News/NewsDetail.aspx?id=64532 Tight finish in Pyongyang]. IAAF. Retrieved on 2012-04-21.</ref>
The 2015 marathon was initially closed to foreigners because of concerns about [[Ebola]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Talmadge|first1=Eric|title=N. Korea bars tourists from popular race over Ebola concerns|url=http://www.sfgate.com/news/article/N-Korea-bars-tourists-from-popular-race-over-6095713.php|accessdate=24 February 2015|agency=Associated Press|publisher=San Francisco Chronicle|date=22 February 2015}}</ref> but this decision has since been reversed after the reopening of the North Korean border in March 2015. <ref>{{cite news|last1=Pearson|first1=James|title=North Korea to reopen Pyongyang marathon to foreign runners|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/03/05/us-northkorea-ebola-marathon-idUSKBN0M10CT20150305|accessdate=6 March 2015|publisher=Reuters|date=5 March 2015}}</ref> The marathon was held in 2016, but did not meet [[IAAF]] specifications for a [[IAAF Bronze Label Road Race]] that it had on previous years.<ref>{{Cite web | title = More Than 1,600 Runners Take Part in Pyongyang Marathon | publisher = Associated Press | work = VOA | date = 10 April 2016 | accessdate = 24 April 2016 | url = http://www.voanews.com/content/pyongyang-marathon-runners/3278426.html }}</ref>
